# Command lnav

## What does this command do:

LNAV -- The Logfile Navigator, log file viewer for the terminal.

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: curl -sSfL https://github.com/tstack/lnav/releases/download/v0.14.0/lnav-0.14.0-linux-musl-x86_64.zip -o /tmp/lnav.zip && unzip /tmp/lnav.zip -d /tmp/lnav-install && mv /tmp/lnav-install/lnav-0.14.0/lnav ~/.local/bin/lnav && chmod +x ~/.local/bin/lnav
For Raspberry Pi install using: curl -sSfL https://github.com/tstack/lnav/releases/download/v0.14.0/lnav-0.14.0-linux-musl-arm64.zip -o /tmp/lnav.zip && unzip /tmp/lnav.zip -d /tmp/lnav-install && mv /tmp/lnav-install/lnav-0.14.0/lnav ~/.local/bin/lnav && chmod +x ~/.local/bin/lnav
For Mac install using: brew install lnav

## Command path

For Fedora run: ~/.local/bin/lnav
For Raspberry Pi run: ~/.local/bin/lnav
For Mac run: /opt/homebrew/bin/lnav

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/tstack/lnav

## Command options

  lnav [options] [logfile1 logfile2 ...]

  -h         Print help, then exit
  -H         Display the internal help text (full key bindings and commands)
  -V         Print version information

  -S, --since  Only index log content since this time
  -U, --until  Only index log content until this time
  -r           Recursively load files from the given directory hierarchies
  -R           Load older rotated log files as well
  -c cmd       Execute a command after files are loaded
  -f file      Execute commands from the given file
  -e cmd       Execute a shell command-line (watch its output)
  -t           Treat stdin as a log file
  -n           Run without the curses UI (headless mode)
  -N           Do not open the default syslog file if no files given
  -q           Do not print informational messages
  -W           Print warnings about lnav's configuration

  -i           Install format files; pass 'extra' for third-party formats
  -m           Management command-line mode (configuration)
  -I dir       Additional configuration directory
  -u           Update formats installed from git repositories

## Key bindings (inside lnav)

  ?            View/leave online help
  q            Quit
  /            Search (forward)
  n / N        Next / previous search match
  g / G        Jump to top / bottom
  e / E        Next / previous error
  w / W        Next / previous warning
  f / F        Next / previous log file
  SPACE        Page down
  b            Page up
  :            Enter lnav command prompt
  ;            Enter SQL query prompt

## Examples

# Open syslog (default)
lnav

# Open all logs in /var/log
lnav /var/log

# Watch output of a command
lnav -e 'make -j4'

# Pipe stdin into lnav
journalctl -f | lnav -t

# Load rotated logs recursively
lnav -Rr /var/log/nginx/

# Run headless (no curses UI)
lnav -n /var/log/syslog

# Filter to errors only after loading
lnav -c ':filter-in error' /var/log/syslog

# Management mode
lnav -m config get
